items.content: T wo people were left trapped and multiple have been seriously injured after a collision between a bus and a car in Sydney.Emergency services responded to a crash on the M2 at Macquarie Park in the city's north-west about 3.40pm today after a bus rear-ended a SUV.The bus driver and one passenger were left trapped and were rescued following a "complex" operation, Fire and Rescue NSW Zone Commander Joshua Turner said.READ MORE: Optus crisis deepens as telco reveals it missed warnings The trapped driver and passenger have since been taken to hospital. READ MORE: Albanese touches down in New York ahead of first meeting with Trump Another seven people suffered minor injuries. Five people in the SUV, including two children, walked away from the crash.The remaining 27 passengers have been transferred to a replacement bus.Police described the rescue as having a "very good outcome". Motorists in the area were warned of significant traffic impacts. The exact cause of the crash is still under investigation. items.title: Simone tried to dial triple zero six times after her husband collapsed
items.standfirst: T he South Australian said her phone was impacted by the Optus outage last week.
items.content: A South Australian woman said she tried to desperately call triple zero six times after her husband collapsed suddenly during the Optus outage.Optus customer Simone Porcaro's husband Dave slipped into unconsciousness after suffering a cellulitis infection.The father-of-two could have gone into septic shock if it wasn't for their young daughter's quick thinking.READ MORE: Queensland man's body returned from Bali with vital organ missing Simone is a Optus customer – but Dave is not." I just kept trying to dial, just freaking out, what were we going to do?" Simone told 9News." It was my seven-year-old daughter that had actually suggested using dad's phone, so we found it underneath him because he was collapsed."Simone and her family are just some of the many Australians who were impacted by the Optus outage on Thursday.A 68-year-old Adelaide woman died from a medical episode when she was unable to get through to triple zero."She was the most altruistic and caring person I've ever known," her husband told 9News.READ MORE: Optus crisis deepens as telco reveals it missed warnings READ MORE: Albanese touches down in New York ahead of first meeting with Trump Optus chief executive Stephen Rue today confirmed the telco had found a further three cases, additional to the two announced yesterday, where customers had complained that they could not call triple zero.Rue said the calls were not adequately escalated within Optus' system, meaning the telco was unaware of a major systemic failure until after 13 hours. The inability to call triple zero affected South Australia, Western Australia and the Northern Territory between 12.30am and 1.30pm on Thursday.A total of three deaths have have so far linked to the outage.A fourth, the death of an eight-week-old baby boy in Adelaide's north, was originally linked but South Australian police have said they believe the outage is unlikely to have contributed to the infant's death.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. clusters.title: Optus outage 'unlikely' to have contributed to eight-week-old baby's death
clusters.neutral_headline: Optus Outage and Baby's Death, Wider Impact Revealed

items.title: Optus outage 'unlikely' to have contributed to eight-week-old baby's death
items.standfirst: A critical outage in the telco giant's network meant Triple Zero calls in South Australia, Western Australia and the Northern Territory were blocked
items.content: An initial investigation has revealed the death of an eight-week-old baby on Thursday was unlikely to have been contributed to by a triple zero outage on the Optus network.A critical outage in the telco giant's network meant triple zero calls in South Australia, Western Australia and the Northern Territory were blocked, with the company announcing it had contributed to three deaths; a fourth was later confirmed by WA Premier Roger Cook.One of the initial deaths announced by Optus was that of an eight-month-old baby boy in Gawler, north of Adelaide.Opinion: Optus has many questions to answer after another staggering failureThe boy's grandmother had initially told police she had tried to call triple zero on her mobile phone after realising her grandson was not breathing.However, a statement from South Australia Police today has shed more light on the incident, revealing it was likely not a factor behind the infant's tragic death."While the family was impacted by the Optus outage, it appears at this stage it is unlikely to have contributed to the death," the statement said."When her call was not connected, she immediately used another mobile telephone in the house and was successfully connected to triple zero.READ MORE: 'I'm absolutely disgusted': South Australian man couldn't call for ambulance during Optus outage"The preliminary investigations indicate the child's death is not due to any delay in SAAS [emergency services] attending the Mulga St house, despite the failure of the first attempt to call 000."SA Police said it did not usually make public comments such as this, but believed the public interest in the story meant transparency was required.They confirmed a full investigation was being provided to the coroner, who will decide whether an inquest will be required.Police also said the investigation into other death in the state connected to the outage, a 68-year-old woman from Queenstown, was still ongoing.Optus chief executive Stephen Rue is scheduled to address the media at 3pm AEST today.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone.
